# IAAA and Broken Access Control Notes

---

# What is IAAA?

IAAA stands for:

1. Identification
2. Authentication
3. Authorization
4. Accounting

These are important security concepts used in cybersecurity and web applications.

---

# 1. Identification

Identification means telling the system who you are.

## Example

```text
Username: shafiq123
```

The system now knows which user is trying to log in.

---

# 2. Authentication

Authentication checks whether the user is real or not.

Usually done using:
- Password
- OTP
- Fingerprint
- Face ID

## Example

```text
Username: shafiq123
Password: mypass123
```

If the password is correct, the user is authenticated.

---

# 3. Authorization

Authorization checks what the user is allowed to access after login.

## Example

| User Role | Permission |
|------------|------------|
| Admin | Delete users |
| Student | View courses |
| Teacher | Upload marks |

A student cannot access admin features.

---

# 4. Accounting

Accounting records user activities.

It stores:
- Login time
- Logout time
- IP address
- User actions

## Example

```text
User shafiq123 logged in at 10:30 AM
Downloaded report.pdf
Logged out at 11:00 AM
```

This helps in monitoring and auditing.

---

# What is Broken Access Control?

Broken Access Control happens when users can access resources or data they should not access.

It is one of the most dangerous web vulnerabilities.

---

# Example of Broken Access Control

Suppose a website URL is:

```text
https://example.com/account/1001
```

A user changes it to:

```text
https://example.com/account/1002
```

If the user can see another person's account information, this is Broken Access Control.

---

# Real-Life Example

A student changes:

```text
/student/result/15
```

to:

```text
/student/result/16
```

and views another student's result.

This is unauthorized access.

---

# Types of Broken Access Control

## 1. Horizontal Privilege Escalation

One user accesses another user's data.

### Example

User A views User B's profile.

---

## 2. Vertical Privilege Escalation

A normal user gains admin access.

### Example

```text
/admin/dashboard
```

---

# What is A07: Authentication Failures?

A07 is part of the OWASP Top 10 vulnerabilities.

It refers to weak authentication and login security.

Attackers can:
- Steal passwords
- Bypass login systems
- Hijack user accounts

---

# Common Authentication Issues

## 1. Weak Passwords

### Bad Example

```text
123456
password
admin
```

These passwords are easy to guess.

---

## 2. No Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)

Using only passwords is weak security.

### Better Security

- Password + OTP
- Password + Fingerprint

---

## 3. Password Stored in Plain Text

### Wrong Method

```text
password = "mypassword123"
```

If the database leaks, attackers can see passwords.

### Correct Method

Store hashed passwords instead of plain text passwords.

---

## 4. Brute Force Attack

Attackers try many passwords repeatedly.

## Example

```text
admin123
admin1234
admin@123
```

---

## 5. Session Hijacking

Attackers steal session cookies and access accounts without passwords.

---

# Prevention Methods

## Preventing Broken Access Control

- Check user permissions properly
- Use role-based access control
- Deny access by default
- Validate every request on the server side

---

## Preventing Authentication Failures

- Use strong passwords
- Enable MFA
- Hash passwords
- Limit login attempts
- Use secure session management

